display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> does not have the intermediate value property. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is not connected, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{1},U_{2}\subseteq  X]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link
type="local"
href="gt-000S.xml"
addr="gt-000S"
title="Separated space">separation</fr:link>. Define a function <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> by
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[f(x) = \begin {cases}0 & \hbox {if }x\in  U_{1}\\ 1 & \hbox {if }x\in  U_{2}.\end {cases}]]></fr:tex>
Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is continuous, since for every open subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A\subseteq \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, the preimage <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(A)]]></fr:tex> is open (by <fr:link
type="local"
href="gt-000Q.xml"
addr="gt-000Q"
title="A function is continuous iff preimage of open subsets are open">A function is continuous iff preimage of open subsets are open</fr:link>). However, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f(X)]]></fr:tex> is not an interval, so we found a counter-example needed to conclude <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> fails to have the intermediate value property.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
